tool.summary:
Computes a ratio between the three dimensional surface area and the planar area of the surface, and optionally also provides the surface area itself. This tool uses a novel methodology to develop a surface area dataset, by triangulating the surface grid, and computing the projected area of each triangular grid, and comparing that to the planar area of a surface. The output values represent ratios between the surface area and planar area, typically ranging from 1 in flat areas to 4 in areas of high variation. This technique was developed by Jeff Jenness, and operates on a 3x3 neighborhood, using the triangulated area of each adjacent cell and applying the pythagorean theorem to compute the surface area.

By default, the planar area of each grid cell is corrected by dividing the cell area by the cosine of slope. Without this correction, the planar area of each grid cell is projected onto a horizontal plane and thus arbitrarily coupled with the actual slope of the bathymetric surface. Dividing cell area by the cosine of slope avoids this coupling while maintaining the independance of surface area and planar area. The resulting ratio of surface area to corrected planar area is also known as arc-chord ratio (ACR) rugosity. For more information on this metric please see Du Preez (2014).

Note: In older versions of BTM, the default behavior of this tool was to not correct planar area for slope. To recreate workflows from previous versions of BTM, uncheck "Correct Planar Area for Slope" to turn off the correction.

Note: in older versions of BTM, this tool was labeled 'rugosity', but that label has been deprecated as this technique is only one of many possible approaches to compute rugosity, or surface roughness, and newer versions of BTM support a variety of approaches for computing surface roughness.

References:

Jenness, Jeff S. "Surface Areas and Ratios from Elevation Grid (surfgrids.avx) extension for ArcView 3.x, v.1.2. Jenness Enterprises. Available at: http://www.jennessent.com/arcview/surface_areas.htm

Jenness, Jeff S. "Calculating landscape surface area from digital elevation models." Wildlife Society Bulletin 32.3 (2004): 829-839.

Du Preez, C. "A new arc-chord ratio (ACR) rugosity index for quantifying three-dimensional landscape structural complexity." Landscape Ecology. 2014, 30, 181–192.
